Predict Diabetes Risk Score based on Health, Lifestyle, Medical parameters

Objective

Develop a diabetes risk score prediction model that considers persons demographic, hereditary, physiology, lifestyle, and medical parameters. Rather than predicting the likelihood of diabetes, the goal is to generate a risk score and demonstrate how key factors influence that score using explainable AI (SHAP / LIME).

1) Perform EDA on Raw data

2) Data Cleansing / Preprocessing (missing values, outliers)

3) Feature Engineering (derived features, composite scores)

4) Data Split: Training / Test

5) Normalize and Enconde Features only on Training data

6) Address Data Imbalance (SMOTE) only on Training data

7) Dimensionality Reduction / Feature Selection

8) Build Ensemble Model (RF and XGBoost)

9) Training and Hyperparameter Tuning

10) Validation and Evaluation

11) Integrate Explainable AI

Dataset Details

  • NHANES dataset for 2021-2023
  • It provides separate XPT files for Demographics, Physical Parameters (BMI, Waist Circumference), Lifestyle (Physical Activity, Smoking, Alcohol), and Medical Parameters (Laboratory: Glycohemoglobin, Fasting Glucose, Insulin, HDL, LDL, Triglycerides).
  • The XPT files were converted to CSV files and were merged into a single dataset.
  • The attributes inflencing the diabetes were retained and others were removed.
  • The target variable diabetes_y_n has 2 classes. 0 is for no diabetes, and 1 is for prediabetes or diabetes.
  • Total number of attributes/fields: 34

Source: https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/continuousnhanes/default.aspx?Cycle=2021-2023

# 1. bmi: String decimals  float
df['BMXBMI'] = pd.to_numeric(df['BMXBMI'], errors='coerce')
print(f"BMXBMI: {df['BMXBMI'].dtype} | NaNs: {df['BMXBMI'].isna().sum()}")

# 2. moderate_ltpa_unit: Units  numeric (D=0, W=1, M=2, Y=3)
unit_map = {'D': 0, 'W': 1, 'M': 2, 'Y': 3, np.nan: -1}
df['PAD790U_num'] = df['PAD790U'].map(unit_map).astype('Int64')  # Nullable int
print(f"PAD790U_num unique: {df['PAD790U'].value_counts().sort_index()}")

# 3. Sleep times: HH:MM  decimal hours
def parse_time_to_hours(time_str):
    """Convert '07:30'  7.5 hours"""
    if pd.isna(time_str):
        return np.nan
    try:
        h, m = map(int, str(time_str).split(':'))
        return h + m / 60.0
    except:
        return np.nan

df['SLQ300_hours'] = df['SLQ300'].apply(parse_time_to_hours)
df['SLQ310_hours'] = df['SLQ310'].apply(parse_time_to_hours)

# Drop originals, keep engineered
df = df.drop(['PAD790U', 'SLQ300', 'SLQ310'], axis=1)

# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
df2 = df

Feature set shape before engineering: (11933, 34)

Create a compsoste score: simple metabolic risk index

In[23]:
print("Feature set shape before engineering:", df2.shape)

# Example composite score: simple metabolic risk index

for col in ["BMXBMI", "BMXWAIST", "BPXOSY1", "LBXTC"]:
    if col not in df2.columns:
        print(f"Warning: {col} not in dataset; skipping composite score.")
        break
else:
    df2["metabolic_risk_score"] = (
        (df2["BMXBMI"] - df2["BMXBMI"].mean()) / df2["BMXBMI"].std() +
        (df2["BMXWAIST"] - df2["BMXWAIST"].mean()) / df2["BMXWAIST"].std() +
        (df2["BPXOSY1"] - df2["BPXOSY1"].mean()) / df2["BPXOSY1"].std() +
        (df2["LBXTC"] - df2["LBXTC"].mean()) / df2["LBXTC"].std()
    )

print("Feature set shape after engineering:", df2.shape)

5) Normalize + Encode Features

Normalization

  • This steps ensures that diabetes risk model learns equally from all features (HbA1c, BMI, age, etc.) regardless of their original scales.
  • Without normalization, features like Glucose (mg/dL) and BMI may dominate simply because they have larger numeric ranges.
  • Normalization ensures each feature contributes proportionally.
  • SMOTE and most models require numeric, and scaled inputs.

Encode Categorical Features

    1. One-hot encoding for nominal categories (e.g., ethnicity), 2) Label encoding or embeddings for ordinal categories.

Note

  • For this dataset, all are numeric after our conversions, so encoding is already implicit. We focus on scaling (StandardScaler).
In[26]:
num_cols_train = X_train.columns  # all numeric at this point

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[num_cols_train])
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test[num_cols_train])

X_train_scaled = pd.DataFrame(X_train_scaled, columns=num_cols_train, index=X_train.index)
X_test_scaled = pd.DataFrame(X_test_scaled, columns=num_cols_train, index=X_test.index)

print("Scaling complete. Mean/std (train):\n")
print(X_train_scaled.describe().loc[["mean", "std"]].round(2))

7) Dimensionality Reduction / Feature Selection

  • PCA reduces noise, improves interpretability, and expedites training

  • Explained variance ratio indicates how much of the total variability in the data is captured by each principal component. In other words, it measures information retained after dimensionality reduction
In[28]:
pca = PCA(n_components=0.95, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train_bal)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test_scaled)

print("Original features:", X_train_scaled.shape[1],
      " PCA components:", X_train_pca.shape[1])

print("Explained variance:", pca.explained_variance_ratio_.sum().round(3))

Original features: 34  PCA components: 27
Explained variance: 0.96

PCA Loadings

Each principal component is a weighted combination of the original features. We can extract these weights (loadings) to see which features contribute most to each component.

In[32]:
loadings = pd.DataFrame(
    pca.components_.T,  # transpose so rows = features
    columns=[f"PC{i+1}" for i in range(pca.n_components_)],
    index=X_train.columns
)

#print(loadings.head())

Contribution of each feature to overall variance

In[33]:
feature_importance = (loadings**2).dot(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)

# Sort by importance
feature_importance = feature_importance.sort_values(ascending=False)
#print(feature_importance)

Visualize Feature Importance

In[34]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

feature_importance.plot(kind="bar", figsize=(12,6))
plt.title("Feature Importance after PCA")
plt.ylabel("Contribution to Explained Variance")
plt.show()

8) Build Ensemble Models (RF, XGBoost)

Since the goal is to generate a risk score, not binary classification so we will be considering probability outputs as the risk score (e.g., predicted probability of diabetes).

9) Train + Hyperparameter Tuning

  • Train with cross-validation (e.g., Stratified K-Fold) to maintain class ratios.

  • Hyperparameter tuning: Use GridSearchCV / Optuna / Bayesian optimization for best hyperparameters.

10) Validation + Evaluation

11) Integrate Explainable AI (SHAP, LIME)

  • Global Interpretability: SHAP summary plots show top risk factors across population. Feature importance ranking

  • Local Interpretability: SHAP force plots or LIME explain individual patients risk score
